00:18:30,870 --> 00:18:32,860
. . .when the light
catches it just right?

263
00:18:33,190 --> 00:18:34,860
She's really quite beautiful.

264
00:18:35,630 --> 00:18:38,220
Of course, you can't depend
on that light.

265
00:18:38,470 --> 00:18:40,820
The wedding is a month from today.

266
00:18:41,630 --> 00:18:43,820
The invitations will be
mailed tonight.

267
00:18:44,070 --> 00:18:45,820
Ever taste her chicken?

268
00:18:47,190 --> 00:18:50,860
She does spectacular
things with a chicken.

269
00:18:52,150 --> 00:18:54,740
And l love a chicken made at home.

270
00:18:56,710 --> 00:18:59,820
This is the ring your grandfather
gave to your grandmother.

271
00:19:00,190 --> 00:19:01,910
She wants you to
give it to Susan.

272
00:19:04,150 --> 00:19:06,180
This is to marry one girl?

273
00:19:07,470 --> 00:19:08,420
Don't do this to me.

274
00:19:08,630 --> 00:19:11,900
l've been waiting for you
to grow up. l can't wait any longer.

275
00:19:13,470 --> 00:19:15,700
Congratulations, Father, you win.

276
00:19:15,910 --> 00:19:18,340
l had every intention of winning.

277
00:19:18,630 --> 00:19:20,350
Congratulations to you, Arthur.

278
00:19:20,590 --> 00:19:23,180
You're going to be wealthy
for the rest of your life.

279
00:19:23,390 --> 00:19:25,260
That's all l've ever wanted to be.

280
00:19:32,790 --> 00:19:35,900
l'll take three dozen of these shirts.
Assorted colors.

281
00:19:36,190 --> 00:19:37,300
l hate my father.

282
00:19:37,550 --> 00:19:39,580
Then purchase four dozen.

283
00:19:40,350 --> 00:19:41,700
Four dozen.

284
00:19:43,110 --> 00:19:43,940
And l want. . .

285
00:19:44,230 --> 00:19:46,620
. . . 1 4 of these sweaters, all green.

286
00:19:46,830 --> 00:19:48,420
-All green?
-l don't wear sweaters.

287
00:19:48,870 --> 00:19:50,430
Send them to
my address, will you?

288
00:19:52,670 --> 00:19:54,660
What else can l buy, Hobson?

289
00:20:02,110 --> 00:20:04,180
Hobson! Did you see that?!

290
00:20:06,830 --> 00:20:07,900
She stole that tie!

291
00:20:08,110 --> 00:20:10,460
lt's a perfect crime!
Girls don't wear ties.

292
00:20:11,230 --> 00:20:14,420
Although some do. lt's not a perfect
crime, but it's a good crime.

293
00:20:14,670 --> 00:20:17,500
lf she murdered the tie
it'd be a perfect crime.

294
00:20:17,750 --> 00:20:19,420
Why are you so happy
about all this?

295
00:20:20,830 --> 00:20:22,860
The man following her
is a security guard.

296
00:20:23,110 --> 00:20:24,460
We've got to be calm!

297
00:20:24,830 --> 00:20:26,550
lsn't she beautiful? Jesus!

298
00:20:26,790 --> 00:20:29,260
May l ask what have
we to do with this?

299
00:21:08,750 --> 00:21:09,940
l beg your pardon, miss.

300
00:21:10,190 --> 00:21:12,460
l'm the security guard
in the store.

301
00:21:13,590 --> 00:21:14,500
You don't need the badge.

302
00:21:14,750 --> 00:21:16,980
No customer would
wear that jacket.

303
00:21:18,430 --> 00:21:19,750
l must look in the bag.

304
00:21:19,990 --> 00:21:21,630
l saw you put something in it.

305
00:21:24,390 --> 00:21:26,220
You got trouble, mister.

306
00:21:26,550 --> 00:21:29,300
You'll never work on the East Coast
again. What's your name?

307
00:21:29,510 --> 00:21:30,700
She's sensational!

308
00:21:30,950 --> 00:21:33,590
She does have a certain
Eleanor Roosevelt quality.

309
00:21:33,830 --> 00:21:35,020
What's your address?

310
00:21:35,590 --> 00:21:37,540
The address, Chester!
l'm not fooling!

311
00:21:37,830 --> 00:21:39,620
l saw you put a tie in that bag!

312
00:21:39,830 --> 00:21:41,150
What did you say?!

313
00:21:41,910 --> 00:21:43,700
All right, that's it!
l want a cop!

314
00:21:43,950 --> 00:21:45,620
Get me a cop!
We need a cop here!

315
00:21:45,870 --> 00:21:47,540
Don't move from where you are.

316
00:21:47,790 --> 00:21:49,300
l don't want you out of my sight!

317
00:21:49,550 --> 00:21:51,190
Get me a cop!
Get your hands off me.

318
00:21:52,150 --> 00:21:54,060
l'm Arthur Bach.
l'll straighten this out.

319
00:21:54,270 --> 00:21:56,990
Mr. Bach, you really should
stay out of this.

320
00:21:57,190 --> 00:21:59,060
Well, he's in it, Chester.
Tell him, Alfred.

321
00:22:00,150 --> 00:22:02,300
l know this woman.
We're shopping together.

322
00:22:02,550 --> 00:22:03,660
Where the hell have you been?

323
00:22:03,910 --> 00:22:05,470
l'm sorry darling.
l got caught up.

324
00:22:05,670 --> 00:22:06,700
She's a friend, Mr. Bach?

325
00:22:06,910 --> 00:22:09,630
He just said that, Chester.
You're such a schmuck.

326
00:22:10,190 --> 00:22:11,540
l asked her to pick out a tie.

327
00:22:11,750 --> 00:22:13,340
l was going to put it on my bill.

328
00:22:13,590 --> 00:22:16,020
-You didn't pay for it?
-l forgot. l'm sorry.

329
00:22:17,790 --> 00:22:20,820
Chester, what can l say?
l had no idea.

330
00:22:21,070 --> 00:22:22,790
May l look at the tie?

331
00:22:28,830 --> 00:22:31,020
Oh, God, that's really lovely.

332
00:22:31,270 --> 00:22:34,020
-l hope you like it.
-You're really wonderful.

333
00:22:38,350 --> 00:22:40,140
Not in front of
all these people, dear.

334
00:22:40,430 --> 00:22:41,750
They might think you're an animal.

335
00:22:41,990 --> 00:22:43,660
Mr. Bach, you understand,
it's my job.

336
00:22:44,030 --> 00:22:46,830
Would you ask the lady at
the counter to put this on my bill?

337
00:22:48,390 --> 00:22:50,900
l'll take care of it, Mr. Bach.
Thank you very much.

338
00:23:00,950 --> 00:23:02,270
Were you scared?

339
00:23:08,190 --> 00:23:10,220
Why are you smiling
at me like that?

340
00:23:12,390 --> 00:23:13,260
l see.

341
00:23:13,750 --> 00:23:15,230
You're a little strange. . .

342
00:23:15,470 --> 00:23:16,700
. . .but cute.
How are you?

343
00:23:18,230 --> 00:23:22,020
Have a nice day. Thank you very much.
l'll go to the bus stop now.

344
00:23:24,670 --> 00:23:26,100
Why did you steal that tie?

345
00:23:26,790 --> 00:23:27,980
l don't know.

346
00:23:28,230 --> 00:23:29,660
l'm a wonderful person!

347
00:23:30,790 --> 00:23:32,020
l'm serious.

348
00:23:32,830 --> 00:23:35,180
l'll be with you in a minute.
He's getting on my nerves.

349
00:23:38,270 --> 00:23:40,380
Will you stop smiling
at me like that?

350
00:23:40,990 --> 00:23:43,220
You look like
one of Santa's helpers.

351
00:23:44,910 --> 00:23:45,700
ls he with us?

352
00:23:45,950 --> 00:23:48,620
My name is Arthur,
and this is Mr. Hobson.

353
00:23:48,870 --> 00:23:50,270
Good afternoon.

354
00:23:51,590 --> 00:23:53,260
Good afternoon?

355
00:23:54,070 --> 00:23:55,790
My name is Linda.

356
00:23:56,830 --> 00:24:00,340
l'd like to thank you very much.
You did a nice thing.

357
00:24:00,590 --> 00:24:02,420
That was an interesting kiss.

358
00:24:03,510 --> 00:24:06,230
-You kiss your wife like that?
-l'm not married.

359
00:24:08,830 --> 00:24:12,980
Keep smiling. 688-5549.

360
00:24:13,550 --> 00:24:15,270
Don't expect big things
on the first date.

361
00:24:15,510 --> 00:24:18,150
Yes, it's been a distinct
pleasure meeting you.

362
00:24:18,390 --> 00:24:20,620
Arthur, we really must be going.

363
00:24:20,830 --> 00:24:22,820
Thank you for
a memorable afternoon.

364
00:24:23,030 --> 00:24:27,230
Usually one must go to a bowling alley
to meet a woman of your stature.

365
00:24:28,390 --> 00:24:29,710
Wouldn't it be funny
if he called me?

366
00:24:30,150 --> 00:24:34,030
Arthur, l see no reason
for prolonging this conversation.

367
00:24:34,230 --> 00:24:35,500
Unless you're planning. . .

368
00:24:35,710 --> 00:24:38,620
. . .to knock over a fruit stand
later in the evening.

369
00:24:38,910 --> 00:24:40,390
Good luck in prison.

370
00:24:42,590 --> 00:24:43,660
Who was the tie for?

371
00:24:44,070 --> 00:24:45,220
A guy.

372
00:24:45,470 --> 00:24:48,380
Look how he stopped smiling.
My father. lt's his birthday.

373
00:24:48,670 --> 00:24:49,860
What are you doing tomorrow night?

374
00:24:51,230 --> 00:24:52,180
l don't know.

375
00:24:52,630 --> 00:24:54,300
l have plans for tomorrow night.
What should l wear?

376
00:24:54,510 --> 00:24:56,150
Steal something casual.

377
00:24:57,830 --> 00:25:00,020
-l like him.
-Likewise, l'm sure.

378
00:25:00,230 --> 00:25:03,060
l'll have Bitterman
drive you home.

379
00:25:04,830 --> 00:25:06,150
You don't have to do that.

380
00:25:06,390 --> 00:25:08,420
Bitterman doesn't
have to take me.

381
00:25:12,550 --> 00:25:15,220
l really hardly ever
take the bus, ever.

382
00:25:16,190 --> 00:25:19,020
-But it's so hard to get a cab.
-Of course.

383
00:25:20,630 --> 00:25:22,300
l'm sure we know a lot
of the same people.

384
00:25:22,550 --> 00:25:24,060
-Get in.
-Right.

385
00:25:27,230 --> 00:25:30,110
Tell Bitterman where to take you.
And make sure. . .

386
00:25:30,590 --> 00:25:32,980
. . .you give him your address
and phone number.

387
00:25:34,790 --> 00:25:36,620
Take care of her, Bitterman.

388
00:25:38,950 --> 00:25:39,940
Good afternoon!

389
00:25:49,110 --> 00:25:51,220
You'd think they'd never
seen a car before.

390
00:25:51,430 --> 00:25:52,830
Hey lady, where
did you get the car?

391
00:25:53,070 --> 00:25:55,870
Could you children please
allow us our privacy?

392
00:25:59,750 --> 00:26:02,100
Could l sit here until
one of my neighbors walks by?

393
00:26:02,590 --> 00:26:04,980
l want someone l know
to see me get out of this.

394
00:26:05,310 --> 00:26:06,180
l understand.

395
00:26:08,190 --> 00:26:11,070
Here comes Mrs. Nesbit.
This should kill her.

396
00:26:11,430 --> 00:26:13,300
Don't touch the door.
l'll do it.

397
00:26:14,270 --> 00:26:17,620
Mrs. Nesbit deserves
the entire treatment.

398
00:26:24,710 --> 00:26:26,110
Thank you, Bitterman.

399
00:26:27,510 --> 00:26:28,830
Well, hello, Mrs. Nesbit!

400
00:26:29,510 --> 00:26:31,020
Will that be all, madam?

401
00:26:31,270 --> 00:26:32,380
l think so.

402
00:26:32,990 --> 00:26:34,580
Have a nice evening, Mrs. Nesbit.

403
00:26:40,030 --> 00:26:42,420
-Could be a big tie.
-lt is a tie.

404
00:26:43,070 --> 00:26:45,420
Then guessing would be
out of the question.

405
00:26:47,590 --> 00:26:49,310
-lt is a tie!
-Surprise!

406
00:26:50,230 --> 00:26:51,630
l love it!

407
00:26:53,950 --> 00:26:56,020
lt goes with everything l own.

408
00:26:56,710 --> 00:26:57,500
l hope you like it.

409
00:26:57,710 --> 00:27:01,220
lf l don't get a job soon, you may
get it back on your birthday.

410
00:27:02,870 --> 00:27:04,020
Dad, shut up.

411
00:27:05,310 --> 00:27:07,620
A funny thing happened
to me today.

412
00:27:08,870 --> 00:27:10,430
Do you know why. . .

413
00:27:10,670 --> 00:27:12,860
. . .girls marry so badly?

414
00:27:14,750 --> 00:27:16,740
ls this a joke?
Are these Polish girls?

415
00:27:19,670 --> 00:27:23,300
The reason is, there
are so many girls. . .

416
00:27:26,590 --> 00:27:28,380
. . .and so few princes.

417
00:27:30,910 --> 00:27:32,180
You met a prince?

418
00:27:32,830 --> 00:27:35,500
l met a nice guy. With my help,
he could become a prince.

419
00:27:35,750 --> 00:27:37,470
-Who is he?
-Just a guy.

420
00:27:37,710 --> 00:27:38,900
What does he do?

421
00:27:40,670 --> 00:27:41,780
Nothing.

422
00:27:43,870 --> 00:27:47,220
Another beauty.
How does he make a living?

423
00:27:48,710 --> 00:27:50,110
Look, l have to make dinner.

424
00:27:50,750 --> 00:27:53,060
l take it this bum
will be calling you.

425
00:27:56,230 --> 00:27:57,460
Dad, he's a millionaire.

426
00:27:57,870 --> 00:28:00,220
You have my permission
to marry him.

427
00:28:00,710 --> 00:28:02,220
Roses. Yellow.

428
00:28:02,470 --> 00:28:04,980
She'll drop dead. She'll love them.

429
00:28:06,110 --> 00:28:07,590
Yellow roses. Two dozen.

430
00:28:08,830 --> 00:28:10,470
l think something else
would look nice too.

431
00:28:12,230 --> 00:28:13,950
Red roses. With the yellow.

432
00:28:14,270 --> 00:28:16,300
She won't know what hit her!
You'll be aces with her.

433
00:28:17,430 --> 00:28:18,540
You're a nice boy.

434
00:28:18,790 --> 00:28:20,220
Two dozen red, okay?

435
00:28:20,790 --> 00:28:23,380
-Do you know what happened?
-No, l don't.

436
00:28:23,630 --> 00:28:25,660
Yesterday l met her
outside Bergdorf's.

437
00:28:26,910 --> 00:28:28,780
l can't stop
thinking about her!

438
00:28:29,590 --> 00:28:30,620
Are you married?

439
00:28:31,030 --> 00:28:32,350
Once. She's alive.

440
00:28:32,950 --> 00:28:35,830
-What's that?
-A yucca plant.

441
00:28:36,030 --> 00:28:37,670
-l'll take it.
-How many?

442
00:28:38,230 --> 00:28:39,140
Four.

443
00:28:39,350 --> 00:28:41,820
Where were you
when l was selling cars?

444
00:28:42,190 --> 00:28:43,750
How did you know
when you fell in love?

445
00:28:43,990 --> 00:28:45,310
How does anybody know?

446
00:28:45,670 --> 00:28:46,860
l was on a train.

447
00:28:47,110 --> 00:28:48,380
From Washington to New York.

448
00:28:48,590 --> 00:28:49,540
What's that?

449
00:28:49,790 --> 00:28:51,660
-A fern. You need five.
-Right!

450
00:28:52,110 --> 00:28:56,180
A girl got on the train.
Skinny. She gave me a smile.

451
00:28:56,670 --> 00:28:58,900
By Baltimore, l was a dead duck.

452
00:28:59,590 --> 00:29:02,340
Did you whistle a lot?
l find l whistle!

453
00:29:02,630 --> 00:29:03,660
l whistled.

454
00:29:05,950 --> 00:29:08,180
Did you feel funny?
l feel funny.

455
00:29:09,510 --> 00:29:10,940
You may have a cold.

456
00:29:13,790 --> 00:29:17,620
Send all this and anything else
you can think of to this address.

457
00:29:19,230 --> 00:29:20,870
Send 2 dozen roses
to your wife.

458
00:29:21,110 --> 00:29:22,540
The skinny one on the train.

459
00:29:22,790 --> 00:29:24,020
Here, keep the change.

460
00:29:25,470 --> 00:29:26,420
You're the rich one?

461
00:29:26,990 --> 00:29:28,180
The one who drinks?

462
00:29:29,950 --> 00:29:32,510
How does it feel
to have all that money?

463
00:29:33,310 --> 00:29:34,790
lt feels great.

464
00:29:37,350 --> 00:29:39,180
A dumb question.

465
00:29:40,030 --> 00:29:41,820
What do you do?
l've never asked.

466
00:29:42,030 --> 00:29:45,300
l'm an actress.
l mean, l'm studying to be one.

467
00:29:46,910 --> 00:29:48,100
But l'm working as a waitress.

468
00:29:48,350 --> 00:29:50,140
A lot of talented girls do that.

469
00:29:50,950 --> 00:29:52,350
What's it like being a waitress?

470
00:29:52,590 --> 00:29:54,460
lt's fun. l mean, you know.

471
00:29:58,470 --> 00:30:00,620
This guy came in and pulled out--

472
00:30:06,790 --> 00:30:10,020
A guy came into the diner
and pulled out--

473
00:30:18,590 --> 00:30:21,020
-He pulled out what?
-Pulled out a gun!

474
00:30:25,950 --> 00:30:26,900
l love this song!

475
00:30:27,150 --> 00:30:28,630
l love it too!

476
00:30:36,830 --> 00:30:37,940
When do l get a turn?

477
00:30:38,190 --> 00:30:40,700
Can't you see l'm going
for a new world's record?

478
00:30:40,990 --> 00:30:44,020
After only 1 2 games,
l have 80 coupons!

479
00:30:45,550 --> 00:30:48,820
l knew it would be different
spending an evening with a millionaire.

480
00:30:51,070 --> 00:30:54,780
Two more and l'm 20 for 20!
That's another 35 coupons!

481
00:30:56,550 --> 00:30:59,220
Could we have a little quiet here?

482
00:31:00,550 --> 00:31:01,980
You nut!

483
00:31:07,230 --> 00:31:08,660
Look at him with his gun.

484
00:31:10,470 --> 00:31:12,030
Are you cute!

485
00:31:16,190 --> 00:31:17,590
God, l missed!

486
00:31:17,790 --> 00:31:18,580
Nineteen.

487
00:31:20,670 --> 00:31:22,900
For 1 9, you get 1 5 coupons.

488
00:31:27,710 --> 00:31:29,300
We really have to go now.

489
00:31:34,390 --> 00:31:35,870
Space lnvaders!

490
00:31:42,630 --> 00:31:44,700
Do you want the orange one?

491
00:31:46,270 --> 00:31:47,220
Enjoy it!

492
00:31:47,910 --> 00:31:49,260
Now take care of it.

493
00:31:49,510 --> 00:31:50,700
l already named it!

494
00:31:50,910 --> 00:31:54,820
l named it after my grandmother
on my mother's side.

495
00:31:55,230 --> 00:31:56,500
Arthur.

496
00:32:01,950 --> 00:32:04,140
Here's a rose.
l stole it from the restaurant.

497
00:32:06,470 --> 00:32:07,620
Thank you.

498
00:32:08,990 --> 00:32:11,060
l've never taken care of anyone.

499
00:32:11,870 --> 00:32:14,780
Everyone's always taken care of me.

500
00:32:16,030 --> 00:32:18,910
But if you got sick, or anything. . .

501
00:32:20,390 --> 00:32:21,740
. . .l'd take care of you.

502
00:32:22,910 --> 00:32:24,390
Then l'll get sick.

503
00:32:39,550 --> 00:32:42,620
This Vermeer just arrived today.

504
00:32:44,350 --> 00:32:45,670
lt's called. . .

505
00:32:46,470 --> 00:32:49,460
. . . ''Woman Admiring Pearls. ''

506
00:32:50,230 --> 00:32:53,220
The dealer jerked me around
on the price a little.

507
00:32:53,470 --> 00:32:55,260
But what the hell.

508
00:32:55,470 --> 00:32:56,660
We live once.

509
00:33:01,150 --> 00:33:02,420
Martha. . . .

510
00:33:04,830 --> 00:33:06,700
What's the matter, Arthur?

511
00:33:10,270 --> 00:33:12,620
l can't marry Susan Johnson.

512
00:33:14,270 --> 00:33:16,990
-Really?
-l met this girl!

513
00:33:18,270 --> 00:33:22,100
You are a charming boy.
Unfortunately. . .

514
00:33:22,310 --> 00:33:25,660
. . .every time you have an erection,
it makes the papers.

515
00:33:27,230 --> 00:33:30,900
Goodness!
l sound like a dime novel.

516
00:33:32,470 --> 00:33:33,740
Peanuts!

517
00:33:38,630 --> 00:33:41,620
lsn't my grandson handsome, Harriet?

518
00:33:41,870 --> 00:33:43,620
-Yes.
